        <title><m>\S V.9</m>: Derivative Rules</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Motivation: Derivative Rules </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We know derivatives "behave nicely" with addition and constant multiples. That is,
                            <me>
                                \frac{d}{dx} (f(x) + g(x)) = f'(x) + g'(x)
                            </me>
                            and
                            <me>
                                \frac{d}{dx} (cf(x) ) = cf'(x)
                            </me>.
                            What about other combinations of functions?
                            <me>
                                \frac{d}{dx} (f(x) \cdot g(x)) =?
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                \frac{d}{dx} \left(\frac{f(x) }{g(x)}\right) =?
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                \frac{d}{dx} (f(g(x))) =?
                            </me>

                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>The Product Rule</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We used the change in area of a growing rectangle to come up with the <term>product rule</term>:
                            <me>
                                \frac{d}{dx} (f(x) \cdot g(x)) = f'(x)g(x) + f(x)g'(x)
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            For example, <m>\frac{d}{dx} (x^2 \cdot x^3) = 2x \cdot x^3 + x^2 \cdot 3x^2 = 5x^4 </m>. We could 
                            also simplify the product to a single power function and use the power rule to verify this answer.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Practice: The Product Rule</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}(x \cdot \sin(x)) = </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dt}(t^4 \cdot e^t) = </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}(x \cdot \sin(x)) = \sin(x) + x\cos(x)</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dt}(t^4 \cdot e^t) = 4t^3e^t + t^4 e^t </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>The Quotient Rule</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We can use the product rule to derive the quotient rule:
                            <me>
                                \frac{d}{dx} \left(\frac{f(x) }{g(x)}\right) = \frac{f'(x)g(x)-f(x)g'(x)}{(g(x))^2}
                            </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            For example, <m>\frac{d}{dx} \left(\frac{x^7}{x^2}\right) = \frac{7x^6 x^2 - x^7 2x}{x^4} = 5x^4 </m>. We could 
                            also simplify the quotient to a single power function and use the power rule to verify this answer.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Practice: The Quotient Rule</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}\left( \frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)} \right) =</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}\left( \frac{x^2}{e^x} \right) =</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}\left( \frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)} \right) =\frac{\cos^2(x)+\sin^2(x)}{\cos^2(x)}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}\left( \frac{x^2}{e^x} \right) = \frac{2xe^x - x^2e^x}{e^{2x}}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>The Chain Rule</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>f(x) = 3x</m> and <m>g(x) = 2x</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Then <m>\frac{d}{dx}(f(g(x)))= \frac{d}{dx}(3(2x)) = 3 \cdot 2</m>. This captures the essence that
                            the derivative of a composition is the derivative of the outside function times the derivative of the 
                            inside function. More precisely, 
                            <me>
                                \frac{d}{dx} (f(g(x))) =f'(g(x))\cdot g'(x)
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            For example, <m>\frac{d}{dx}(\sin(x^2))= \cos(x^2) \cdot 2x</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Practice: The Chain Rule</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}(e^{2x})=</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dt}(\ln(\cos(t)))=</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}(e^{2x})= e^{2x} \cdot 2</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dt}(\ln(\cos(t)))= \frac{1}{\cos(t)} \cdot (-\sin(t))</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: Putting It All Together</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}(\sin(x^2) \ cdot x^3)=</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}(e^{\sin(x)\cdot \cos(x)})=</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}(\sin(x^2) \ cdot x^3)=\cos(x^2)\cdot 2x \cdot x^3 + \sin(x^2)\cdot 3x^2</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{d}{dx}(e^{\sin(x)\cdot \cos(x)})= e^{\sin(x)\cos(x)} \cdot (\cos^2(x)-\sin^2(x))</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

